example.p:
The column vector of constants, $\vect{b}$, in  is given below, and one solution listed for $\linearsystem{A}{\vect{b}}$ is $\vect{x}$,


\vect{b}&=\colvector{8\\-12\\4}
&
\vect{x}&=\colvector{7\\8\\1\\3}

On the other hand,  is the linear system $\linearsystem{A}{\vect{c}}$, where the vector of constants is

\vect{c}=\colvector{2\\3\\2}

and this system of equations is inconsistent.  This means $\vect{c}\not\in\csp{A}$, for if it were, then it would equal a linear combination of the columns of $A$ and  would lead us to a solution of the system $\linearsystem{A}{\vect{c}}$.

subsection.p:
Employing  we can form the chain of equivalences

\vect{b}\in\csp{A}
\iff
\linearsystem{A}{\vect{b}}\text{ is consistent}
\iff
A\vect{x}=\vect{b}\text{ for some }\vect{x}

Thus, an alternative (and popular) definition of the column space of an $m\times n$ matrix $A$ is

\csp{A}&=
\setparts{
\vect{y}\in\complex{m}
}{
\vect{y}=A\vect{x}\text{ for some }\vect{x}\in\complex{n}
}
=
\setparts{A\vect{x}}{\vect{x}\in\complex{n}}
\subseteq\complex{m}

example.p:
We first show that $\vect{v}=\colvector{18\\-6\\12}$ is in the column space of $A$, $\vect{v}\in\csp{A}$.   says we need only check the consistency of $\linearsystem{A}{\vect{v}}$.  Form the augmented matrix and row-reduce,

\begin{bmatrix}
3 & 2 & 1 & -4 & 18\\
-1 & 1 & -2 & 3 & -6\\
2 & -4 & 6 & -8 & 12
\end{bmatrix}
\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 & 1 & -2 & 6\\
0 & \leading{1} & -1 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}

Now we show that $\vect{w}=\colvector{2\\1\\-3}$ is not in the column space of $A$, $\vect{w}\not\in\csp{A}$.   says we need only check the consistency of $\linearsystem{A}{\vect{w}}$.  Form the augmented matrix and row-reduce,

\begin{bmatrix}
3 & 2 & 1 & -4 & 2\\
-1 & 1 & -2 & 3 & 1\\
2 & -4 & 6 & -8 & -3
\end{bmatrix}
\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 & 1 & -2 & 0\\
0 & \leading{1} & -1 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}
\end{bmatrix}

According to the definition (), the column space of $A$ is

\csp{A}=
\spn{\set{
\colvector{ 2 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ -2 },\,
\colvector{ 4 \\ 2 \\ 0 \\ 2 \\ -4 },\,
\colvector{ 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ -1 \\ 1 },\,
\colvector{ -1 \\ 0 \\ 4 \\ 2 \\ 3 },\,
\colvector{ 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ -1 },\,
\colvector{ 4 \\ 4 \\ 8 \\ 9 \\ -2 },\,
\colvector{ 4 \\ 7 \\ 7 \\ 6 \\ -2 }
}}

The pivot columns are $D=\set{1,\,3,\,4,\,5}$, so we can create the set

T=\set{
\colvector{ 2 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ -2 },\,
\colvector{ 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ -1 \\ 1 },\,
\colvector{ -1 \\ 0 \\ 4 \\ 2 \\ 3 },\,
\colvector{ 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ -1 }
}

and know that $\csp{A}=\spn{T}$ and $T$ is a linearly independent set of columns from the set of columns of $A$.

